text: 🇫🇷 l’actualité française, coincée ces dernières semaines entre denis baupin, les violeurs de la bri et la ligue du lol nous montre une fois de plus l’impunité dans laquelle le patriarcat se complaît. ces hommes qui jouissent de leur statut de dominant et des privilèges qui vont avec depuis qu’ils ont vu le jour se voient aujourd’hui rappelés par la loi. pour certains c’est la surprise, pour d’autres le déni, ou encore l’incompréhension, tant ils ont pris l’habitude de discriminer,  persécuter, violer en se sentant « dans leur droit ». ce qui me donne espoir cependant c’est la preuve du pouvoir de la parole dans ces affaires. ces femmes (et ces hommes parfois) qui ont eu le courage de parler pour faire entendre la vérité et dénoncer, non seulement les harceleurs mais aussi le système de domination patriarcale dans lequel nous vivons, contribuent à amplifier cette prise de conscience massive dont #metoo était l’étincelle. ✨nous sommes encore loin du feu de joie, mais le vent de la révolution souffle sur les braises de l’émancipation 🔥 🔥🔥🔥 🇬🇧 perhaps you heard the recent news of denis baupin, the bri rapists and the ligue du lol, which show us once again the impunity in which the patriarchy mentality imposes itself.  these men who enjoy their dominant status and the privileges that come with since they were born are now reminded by law. for some it is a surprise, for others it is a denial, or even a misunderstanding, as they are so used to discriminate, persecute, rape while feeling "in their right". what gives me hope, however, is the proof of the power of speech in these cases.  these women (and sometimes men) who had the courage to speak out to make the truth heard and denounce, not only the harassers but also the system of patriarchal domination we live in, they contribute to amplify this massive awareness of which #metoo was the spark. ✨ we are still far from the bonfire, but the wind of revolution is blowing over the embers of emancipation 🔥

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i’ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i’m about to go back, knowing what i know, and we’re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump’s election, trumpeted the return of their “populist hero” on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication’s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there’s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i’m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents – on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
installation view:
“our anger runneth over”
“crisis of skin”
“i’m not angry i’m mad as hell”
on view in @rosemarymezadesplas jane anger through feb. 24. 
join us today, sunday, 4-6pm for an art workshop presented by @hayleyferber!
.
open 12-8pm with @rosemarymezadesplas jane anger. pictured here: “our anger runneth over” watercolor on aquaboard, 16x20x2”
rosemary mesa-desplas performing a spoken word piece at last week’s opening reception. the exhibition is on view today, thu-sun, 12-6pm through feb 24.
.
.
jane anger features hand-sewn human hair drawings, watercolors and onsite installations. rosemary meza-desplas’ figurative artworks emphasize line and movement. the title refers to a 16th century pamphlet published in england titled jane anger, her protection for women.

meza-desplas explores the concept of anger as a tool for change by juxtaposing found imagery from social media, art history and mass media. she is interested in how the social movements, women’s marches and #metoo, harnessed anger in order to forefront an array of gender-based burdens. 
this exhibition includes meza-desplas’ most recent drawings which incorporate her gray hair. she has been sewing with her own hair since 2000. her hair is hand-sewn into a variety of grounds with small embroidery needles. meza-desplas’ decision to collect, sort and utilize hair as a vehicle for art-making is informed by socio-cultural symbolism, feminism and body issues, and religious symbolism. hair embodies a dichotomy: it can be sexy and engaging to people, on the other hand, it can be repulsive – like a hair in your soup or a hair on your hotel pillow. 
there are religious connotations to hair which coincide with symbolism reflecting strength, sensuality and reverence; such as delila cutting off samson’s hair and mary magdalen washing the feet of jesus with her hair.

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text: less than 3 weeks until @girlalliance2 takes the stage at @sxswedu!!!!! we’re also so excited to announce that @alexa_curtis will be joining founder @avniiii.s and chief ambassador @sofiamsandrea in this eye-opening discussion about teen sexual harassment, the #metoo movement, and how adults can support teen activists and entrepreneurs! read our full panel description here: boys texting girls to “send nudes” is the new teen flirting ritual. hear two teens share horror stories of how high school is a breeding ground for sexual harassment and why existing adult-made solutions just don’t cut it. learn how they have adapted kathleen reardon’s spectrum for sexual misconduct framework to high school, how their girl alliance ambassadors sparked a cultural shift, and how adults can help unleash the youth voice in fighting sexual harassment and other issues.

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
little things to change the world. like when you see an artist prominently featured (by virtue of the alphabet) in a record or movie store, you can speak with the store owner. maybe they won’t care, but maybe like road runner in se mpls they will pull @ryanadams out of his alphabetical place.

if you’ve got the energy for it, especially if you have the privilege of someone who looks like ryan adams, you can make little changes that fuck shit up in a good way. 
we all take part in normalizing or allowing these sorts of people to keep working and take up space, and we can all take part in pushing back.

my heart goes out to all the women who came forward, and to all the folks who felt they couldn’t speak up. and i hope the folks who have the power to prevent things no longer ignore and validate these sorts of people.

in the words of @_fake_nudes_ :
“none of them held him accountable. they told him, by what they said or what they didn’t, that what he was doing was okay.” #ryanadams #metoomovement #metoo #standwithsurvivors #holdthemaccountable #nomoresilence

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
sunday’s used to be fun days. these days they seem to be more triggering. especially over the last couple years, with news cycle after news cycle breaking, revealing decades of sexual abuse within the church. and, worse than the abuse taking place, the revelation that leadership knew, enabled, and covered it up.
💔
i can’t seem to bring myself to walk into a church building any more. church can be a trauma trigger for some of us. the body keeps the score. i’ve finally allowed myself the safety of being ok with staying home. making that decision has brought me both healing and heartbreak. i’m allowing the space for both. because healing comes in waves...
🌊
healing comes in waves
and maybe today
the wave hits the rocks.
and that’s ok,
that’s ok, darling
you are still healing
you are still healing.
📝

text:
a wonderful and intimate evening with tarana burke (@taranajaneen), the founder of #metoo at the @torontoblackfilmfest. last night, tarana received the toronto black film festival’s social impact award!

she is an amazing woman who has done so much work within community (and for community) to create safe spaces for survivors to share their stories and find hope, humour and healing throughout their journey. 
every #metoo hashtag has a story and we must continue to do the work to lift every voice. we must teach our male-identified children, youth and adults about consent and harm, and we have to keep the conversation going.

#metoo is not a moment, it’s a movement and it is just getting started!

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since day one.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop, has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagate™ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaign’s use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of people’s profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there “could have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheating”. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesday’s hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

text: 초등학교 6학년, 난 아직도 그 느낌이 기억나. 날 만지던 그 손. 아닐꺼라 생각하며 너희를 믿었는데 나중엔 몇몇이 실토했지. 그때의 난 당당하지 못하고 뒤로 숨을 수 밖에 없었어 너무 무서웠거든. 그후 고등학교에 진학하고 같은 학교에서 너희를 봤을 때 진짜 미치겠더라. 너희는 그 일들이 생각 나지 않는 건지, 애써 모른 척 하는 건지. 아무렇지 않게 살아가는 너희가 너무 역겨웠어. 이제는 말할래. 너희들이 한 짓 그거 성추행이야. #metoo #미투캠페인 #withyou

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
in 2014, steve bannon – then executive chairman of the “alt-right” news network breitbart – was christopher wylie’s boss. and robert mercer, the secretive us hedge-fund billionaire and republican donor, was cambridge analytica’s investor. and the idea they bought into was to bring big data and social media to an established military methodology – “information operations” – then turn it on the us electorate.

cambridge analytica’s parent company, scl, had won contracts with the us state department and was pitching to the pentagon, and wylie was genuinely freaked out. - it’s insane, he told me one night. - the company has created psychological profiles of 230 million americans. and now they want to work with the pentagon? it’s like nixon on steroids.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

kumeka came from another universe, and was called here to help setup the conditions for the golden age of atlantis, called here, he came to this universe from places much further developed (determined by the energy who comes through clearest). we are connected to infinite love and knowledge by the "vibrational" umbilical cord of life.

ascended masters are those rays found 8-12, the awakened are accessing these rays and tapping into higher and higher understandings of who we are and where we come from.

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
footage of nigel farage swigging a pint and thanking steve bannon and breitbart for the brexit result was deleted from a breitbart youtube channel, following the data scandal surrounding cambridge analytica.
.
- well done bannon, well done breitbart, the ex-ukip leader announces in the short clip. - you helped with this. hugely.

farage’s nod to steve bannon certainly hasn’t aged well in the context of the recent storm around cambridge analytica’s influence over the eu referendum.

it was revealed that data from 50 million facebook profiles were looked at against the electoral register, and then used to build an algorithm which analyses people’s personality traits in relation to their voting behaviour.

this data could then be used to find potential swing voters and create messages tailored to influence them politically.

the firm’s vice president at the time was steve bannon, who was also head of the right-wing website breitbart and was running donald trump’s campaign to become us president.

inews

text:
how #fauxnews perpetuates white cis-het supremacy and stokes white fear of the “other”: through diligently and intentionally presenting blackness and queerness and refugeeness in the worst possible light, reporting near-exclusively on the negative, while failing to report in any real or meaningful way on the ways toxic patriarchal misogynistic queerphobic whiteness coddles and produces the majority of rapists and mass shooters, all of which results in movements like #metoo, which they only report on when an lgbtqia or black or indigenous or immigrant person stands accused of the crime. 
stop watching faux news. stop buying their white supremacist narrative. stop clicking on their pictures of black and queer and immigrant people doing bad things. stop ignoring their praise and amplification of blatant white supremacists like stephen miller. stop living in their carefully curated white bubble of fear and hatred.

i am not only concerned about the injustice he has done on this case. but what about all of the other child molesters he has helped avoid prison sentences?

i hope and pray that the israeli police will look into all cases that the health minister litzman was involved with to make sure that those who hurt children are held accountable
--- police investigators have central evidence that raises the suspicions against the deputy minister, according to channel 13 news.

many doctors have told yedioth ahronoth over the weekend that leifer's case was not unique. 
a senior health ministry official said that "everyone knows litzman's system. he claims he doesn't interfere, but the message is clear: you must approve the treatment or arrange an appointment. this is against the rules of ethics and good governance. litzman feels he is above the law. no minister before him has acted that way." full story here-

text: know them that labor among you is an admonishment in the scriptures and it wouldn't be there if it weren't absolutely necessary! this means you have to take time to watch and evaluate your leader's (and other members') character. you can only do this with intentionality and  over time. thus, you can't be trusting of church leaders and church members simply because they attend church, say they are called by god, or are able to mimic the behaviors of your assembly. put your pastor and church members under an intense microscope! require them to adhere to your family's safety plan and take note if/when it is violated because their unwillingness to adhere to your requirements indicate a lack of respect and to a greater extent, the possibility that you are dealing with a possible predator. don't get caught off guard due to a perceived sense of trustworthiness because of a church affiliation. also, take note of leaders and members who bounce from congregation to congregation and state to state. check out their history in their previous assemblies. don't take their explanation for why they've left another congregation or state at face value because many of these predators are serial predators. #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #rapevictim #victim #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate #volunteer #activist #superbowl @pros4youth

text: chapter 21: it's not a linear process "once we have more cellular learning materials and more space to consider (due to the repair in the areas of our prefrontal cortex, thanks to paying attention to our body sensations and body in space) we can conceptualize and use more tools, which means we have the capacity to handle more distressing body responses. why does this happen? because our bodies can recognize when we are building resilience, and it wants to heal. as peter levine reminds us in waking the tiger, the body is constantly looking for opportunities to renegotiate trauma. it will hand us these opportunities as it registers our capacity to navigate through them. it will recognize our increased resilience and say to us, "i guess you’re ready for this one now, here you go!" the problem is that we judge this process. we think we should be "done by now," and in doing so we slow the process up. let’s say we we're restoring a house or a car. if we come upon a repair that is a little more complicated or takes a little more time (like when a builder opens up a wall and realizes there are no support beams holding up the house for example), is it helpful to sit and wallow in feeling like we should be done by now? no, but we do it, and that’s ok. we all want a break from time to time. but it is important to recognize that there really isn’t a finish line. just like a house or a car, our bodies will always need maintenance, it’s just the first part of the restoration that is likely to have us throwing our hands up in the air saying "oh my god i just wanna be done already!" once you realize there is no done, the job becomes a whole lot easier."#loveyourself #strength #traumarecovery #faith #resilience #trauma #traumarecovery #mindfulness #women #womenempowerment #woman #men #metoo #yoga #inspiration #instagood #community

text:
dzięki uprzejmości @wydawnictwomuza mogłam przeczytać książkę jeszcze przed jej premierą.

pewnego dnia amerykański rząd wydaje dekret, którym skazuje połowę społeczeństwa na milczenie. kobietom wolno wypowiedzieć tylko 100 słów dziennie. ale to dopiero początek... time określił książkę jako głos epoki #metoo 
co by się stało, gdyby kobietom odebrano prawo głosu, gdyby naprawdę mogły wypowiedzieć tylko 100 słów dziennie? 
autorka uważa, że jeśli prawa kobiet na całym świecie nadal będą łamane, z czasem do tego dojdzie - kobiety zostaną bez prawa głosu.

szum jaki został wywołany w stosunku do książki zachęcał do szybkiego przeczytania. autorka od samego początku potrafi zaciekawić czytelnika, akcja nie jest rozwleczona, a rozdziały krótkie bez zbędnych opisów i koloryzowania. to na początku.

niestety... z każdą kolejną stroną książka staje się bardziej monotonna, a wybory głównej bohaterki coraz mniej zrozumiałe dla czytelnika. zakończenie nie jest ani trochę zaskakujące, jest wręcz do przewidzenia po przeczytaniu niewielkiej części książki. 
sam zamysł książki był super, ale brakowało tego feministycznego boom i walki o wolność, na które się zanosiło.

#wydawnictwomuza #vox #książka #czytam #czytaniejestsexy #igreads #bookstagram #booklover #feminist

tweet_full:
dzięki uprzejmości @wydawnictwomuza mogłam przeczytać książkę jeszcze przed jej premierą.

pewnego dnia amerykański rząd wydaje dekret, którym skazuje połowę społeczeństwa na milczenie. kobietom wolno wypowiedzieć tylko 100 słów dziennie. ale to dopiero początek... time określił książkę jako głos epoki #metoo 
co by się stało, gdyby kobietom odebrano prawo głosu, gdyby naprawdę mogły wypowiedzieć tylko 100 słów dziennie? 
autorka uważa, że jeśli prawa kobiet na całym świecie nadal będą łamane, z czasem do tego dojdzie - kobiety zostaną bez prawa głosu.

szum jaki został wywołany w stosunku do książki zachęcał do szybkiego przeczytania. autorka od samego początku potrafi zaciekawić czytelnika, akcja nie jest rozwleczona, a rozdziały krótkie bez zbędnych opisów i koloryzowania. to na początku.

niestety... z każdą kolejną stroną książka staje się bardziej monotonna, a wybory głównej bohaterki coraz mniej zrozumiałe dla czytelnika. zakończenie nie jest ani trochę zaskakujące, jest wręcz do przewidzenia po przeczytaniu niewielkiej części książki. 
sam zamysł książki był super, ale brakowało tego feministycznego boom i walki o wolność, na które się zanosiło.

#wydawnictwomuza #vox #książka #czytam #czytaniejestsexy #igreads #bookstagram #booklover #feminist

text:
highlights of today's weekly program (17th of feb, '19)
.
lecture 2: living during an era of trials and temptations by dr. raziul islam
.
what is "fitnah"? #fitnah means #trials, sufferings, #temptations, spreading of #evil.
.
• everything in the universe has a set of rules & laws which they cannot transgress.
• prophet #muhammad (pbuh) warned us of fitnah, especially during the end times, which will be abundant and difficult to stay away from. it will surround us from all sides, as we see today.
• we must try to save ourselves from these trials of fitnah.
.
⏹️ types of fitnah:-
.
1. wealth:
• as much as #wealth is essential for survival, it also easily corrupts a person's heart.
• one must always keep in mind the rights of others over our wealth.
• it's not bad to have money in your pocket, but it's wrong to have #money in your heart.
.
2. neglecting the difference between halal & haram:-
• the #qur'an has made very clear what's halal & what's haram.
• don't stray too close to the boundary of #haram, for it won't take long for you to fall into it.
.
3. freedom:
• freedom is acceptable to a certain extent. you do not have the freedom to do whatever you want.
• people, in the name of #freedom, are doing unethical & unacceptable things. hence, freedom has to have a limit
.
4. intermixing of genders:
• " #metoo " is what happens when you normalise male & female intermingling, especially in isolation, for we know that when a male & female are together in seclusion, the third among them is satan.
.
5. seclusion:
• the sins we don't commit in public, we must also not commit in private
• this era of the internet has made it easy for people to sin privately.
.
6. narcissism & showing off:
• no, it's not okay to show off your blessings or good deeds to the world.
.
⏹️ to stay away from fitnah, let's hold on tightly to allah's book.
.
.
join us for our weekly programs, every sunday from 10:30 to 12 noon at @jihmarkaz
(near al-shifa hospital, abul fazl enclave).
.
. we @giodelhi are a bunch of young muslimahs, on a journey towards siraat al mustaqeem, being each other's support system❤
.
.
#islam #muslim #muslimah #girl #girls #alhamdulillah #allah #allahuakbar #okhla #del

text:
last day! i’m giving a final walkthrough @edwardhopperhouse at 4pm. 
at the back of the main gallery, the last image you see, is of a female figure staring back. it’s the only painting that hangs on a patch of white wall. she wears a “pink shimmy” similar to the same jo wore in several of the paintings hopper painted, and one she painted of herself. it alludes to ed’s usherette but she returns the gaze, as if she just snapped out of her dreamscape and noticed she was being watched. her hand shifting from thoughtful head rest to reflexive fist. 
the title, “sunwise turn”, is taken from the name of the bookstore where jo exhibited and gained some acclaim, showing her work alongside burchfield and other well know artists of the day. 
but i like the title for the open ended word play. 
sunwise turn, could allude to the old celtic phrase, uttered to ward off the evil eye, it could embrace a turning toward the sun— shadows searching for light and finding it... maybe it alludes to ed as the sun and jo’s dutiful turn towards his career over her own. or maybe it’s more about what’s to come, for us all. 
thank you jo nivison hopper. it’s been so wonderful getting to know you. and special thanks to @etcolleary @gail.levin.art for their scholarship on the hopper’s, jennifer patton and all the wonderful staff and docents at the hopper house, @jillianmcluhan @erikasalus @uhlecia @rainbow_wonder @rdakini @abbeyrosko for all their help along the way.

text:
healing through nature,

an extract from my diary today and a huge breakthrough for me.  i hope that my sharing this with you, that my understanding of this will help someone else out there too. 
i'm not saying it will help everyone but if it helps just one person then its definitely something that should be shared. 
every one of us has the ability to help improve this world and every one of us can gift wisdom and knowledge to another. 
this isn't about being abused, it is about the recovery of it and getting to the point of letting that pain go.

text:
je vais te dire un truc que tu sais déjà. : le soleil et les arcs en ciel, c'est pas le monde. il n' y a pas de vraies tempêtes, de lourdes épreuves. aussi grand et fort que tu sois, la vie te mettra à genoux et te laissera comme ça en permanence si tu la laisses faire. toi, moi, n'importe qui, personne ne frappe aussi fort que la vie. c'est pas d'être un bon cogneur qui compte, l'important c'est de se faire cogner et d'aller quand même de l'avant. c'est de pouvoir encaisser sans jamais flancher. c'est comme ça qu'on gagne.

💜💜💜 #repost @survivorsnetwork ・・・
did you know that we now run a supporters group in hastings and in eastbourne?
💜
it is a safe and confidential space for supporters of anyone who has had unwanted sexual experiences. come together to share strategies and insight on helping loved ones cope with similar issues.
💜
before joining your first session at the group, there’s a 90 minute workshop to attend. this will look at the possible impact of these experiences on the person you care about, but also how this might impact on you.
💜
if you are interested in attending please email admin@survivorsnetwork.org.uk or call 01273 203380, stating which area you are based in.
💜

💜

location: café north, eastbourne, bn21 3hg
💜

text:
sprache verschlagen. ich bin taff, stark (danke, crossfit!), wehre mich. stehe für mich ein. dachte ich - bis heute morgen. bis ich in enger jeans beim bäcker in der schlange stehe, sich ein mann mit mädchen hinter mir einreiht. etwas berührt mich am po, während er einen schritt auf mich und das regal zugeht, das rechts von mir steht. ich schreite zur seite und reagiere nicht weiter, denke es ist seine tasche; denke, er ist unaufmerksam. es passiert ein zweites mal. ich drehe mich um, sehe, dass er keine tasche hat, er aber unbeirrt weiter mit seiner tochter redet, als sei nichts gewesen. bilde ich mir das nur ein? dann bin ich endlich an der reihe und bestelle semmeln. da tritt er erneut so nah an mich heran, presst für eine sekunde seine hüfte an meinen po, ehe er sich dicht rechts neben mich stellt und unbeirrt so tut, als würde er sich das gebäck in der auslage ansehen, den blick wegdreht. und ich? ich schweige. bin irritiert, will keine szene vor seiner tochter machen, die keine 10 jahre alt ist. bin sprachlos. sehe den mann an, der in seiner unschuldigen, langweiligen art keinen zweifel daran lassen will, dass es niemals absichtlich gewesen sein kann, es bestimmt dreimal innerhalb einer minute nur „ein versehen“ war - so versehentlich, dass er es selbst nicht bemerkt hat. ich glaube für einen moment selbst, dass es ein versehen gewesen sein muss. dass er sowas nie tun würde. mich sexuell belästigen, während seine tochter neben ihm steht... und mir verschlägt es die sprache. schnell verlasse ich den laden. sprachlos. schweigend. was ist da gerade passiert? mein sonntagmorgen endete schließlich mit tränen. tränen nicht darüber, dass ein mann mich begrapsch hat - damit kann ich leben. aber tränen über mich selbst, dass ich zu feige war, den mund aufzumachen! wieso habe ich mich nicht gewehrt? nur, weil seine tochter dabei war? welch eine absurde masche, genau darauf abzuzielen....! ein kind derart zu instrumentalisieren ist widerlich. aber was mich wirklich entsetzt, ist meine passivität und flucht. sagte ich nicht, ich sei taff? stehe für mich ein? stattdessen schaue ich sprachlos, beschämt auf meine eigene hilflosigkeit....
#sprachlos #metoo #hilflos

text:
for a long time, i was afraid of my body. i thought that it was my fault that this horror had happened to me. because of this, i tried to hide in plain sight. i couldn’t look myself in the mirror without feeling so much disgust that i had let this happen to me. 
it was not my fault. if you are a victim of sexual assault, please always remember that it isn’t your fault. it was their choice to hurt you. it was their choice, not yours. #metoo

text:
last night at the @torontoblackfilmfest i met @taranajaneen for the first time. she received the inaugural #tbff19 social impact award!!!
as a survivor of child sexual abuse, i left with an elevated sense of pride and hope i had never felt before. most moments when i've thought of what it's meant for me to be a survivor i've often begun from a place of struggle...of pain of what i've had to overcome. this is all incredibly valid. however, this morning, i woke up and my thoughts on survivorhood  had expanded. i woke up thinking of the opportunities being a survivor has afforded me... opportunities for deeper empathy, listening and building the world we want to see with survivors. as tarana said the healing journey... the 'solutions'..must center, must start with, and be led by survivors.tarana left me feeling rejuvenated and more ready than ever to continue to roll up my sleeves and help where and as i can on this life-long journey of surviving, healing and thriving. pain is part of that healing but so is pleasure, humour and togetherness! so is adequate funding to sexual assault, rape crisis centres and women's shelters! yesterday was powerful. tarana spoke unapologetically about centering the lives of women and girls - especially black and brown women and girls. she spoke relentlessly about our healing, our growth and her lifetime dedication to us and to the fight against sexual violence...gender-based violence and the layers of oppression that accompany this. thank you beyond words tarana...thank you for surviving. #metoo #metoomovement

text:
| artwork “psyche presenting venus with water from river styx” by raphael sanzio |  the taskmaster in the story of cupid and psyche was cupid's mother, the love goddess venus. venus had never liked psyche, so the opportunity of putting her to a series of tests gave venus a chance to demand the seemingly impossible. in order for psyche to win back her husband, cupid, venus set four seemingly impossible tasks before psyche: (1)
sorting out a huge pile of seeds, (2)
retrieving the golden fleece, (3)
filling a flask from the water that fills the river styx, and (4)
returning from the underworld with a box of the beauty ointment of persephone.

text:
hey all,
.
i figured i should probably introduce myself. i thought about waiting, but the whole point of this is to find my voice and not be afraid to use it.
.
my name is danielle and i was sexually assaulted the summer before my senior year in college. 10 years later, i am finally willing and able to look it straight on as i try to heal from it.
i refuse to be a victim anymore. 
i am here for any and all of you. ✨🖤
.

text:
#tldr — get your kids outside.
•
my family lived in canada until i was quinn’s age. i spent most of my time outdoors, using my imagination, being wild but always kind-hearted. i climbed trees, ice skated at recess, built forts in our front yard, and played barbies with my big sister in the old greenhouse attached to our garage. we rode our bikes to the corner store and walked to school each day.
by the time i was piper’s age, we had moved back to the states, i had cut bangs to hide my forehead, i had cut my my wrist just to feel something, i had been sexually harassed throughout my fifth grade year by a boy who must have been in a lot of pain. i had a sip of beer at a sleepover and was sick with fear that my parents would find out; knowing god already knew. i watched movies i was too embarrassed to admit i was too afraid to watch. i had vivid nightmares or lay awake for hours trying to count enough sheep to exorcise rosemary’s baby or heeeeere’s johnny from my memory. i was mortified to learn what 69 meant and was teased relentlessly for my ignorance. i tried my first cigarette. i had my first sweet kiss — we were both wearing glasses and sort of bumped faces his name was augustus. i also had my first french kiss — a mess resulting in chapped lips. i said something mean to a girl who threatened to beat me up and i still hold the shame of it. she eventually did beat me up at the summer fun fest so maybe i should stop feeling bad about what i said.
i might have always been an anxious kid, but found comfort in the outdoors, away from mirrors, skin safely hidden in layers. puberty + abuse resulted in years of shame, disgust and disrespect. my flesh, as the gospel said, had ruined everything.
i disconnected from my body when it proved problematic. pimples periods bra straps sweaty armpits hair that i didn’t know what to do with. boobs and a butt that would be ogled and groped and used. i no longer enjoyed being outside because there were no mirrors to check my hair. i hated makeup because i felt fake in it, but i did it anyway because i didn’t know i was pretty without it.

text:
something pretty special went down at @o2forumktown last night. 
hundreds of badass b*tches (mostly women!!) came out to laugh, cry & get righteously angry with @luisaomielan. 
i’ve seen #politicsforbitches at various stages of creation but last night we watched two hours of truth and storytelling by one of my fave comedians ever! it really feels like comedy and feminism are shifting into this new, intersectional space which lifts everyone up but isn’t afraid to tell it like it is. the vibe was ace and the dance party afterwards was lit! 🔥
also a massive shoutout to charlotte - when an agent commits to the power and the love as much as the act, magic happens. super proud to see what @austintalent_ is doing and psyched to be a small part of it with #notflix!! feeling the love and the grrrrlll power vibes! 🤘
.
.
.

text_retweet:
sunday shoutout to @lifecontinuesafter 💛 a beautiful & powerful space for survivors of sexual assault to come together. please check them out - www.lifecontinuesafter.com
❣️
#repost • @lifecontinuesafter “tw: sexual assault // will go live on saturday ❤️❤️after speaking with other survivors and reflecting on my experiences of feeling abandoned by society in my recovery, i realised i could fill the hole that i felt was missing in the recovery process. although they are vital, substantial recovery unfortunately doesn’t often happen in the 8 week therapy sessions that is provided to some on the nhs. after my therapy ended i needed a space to write and to read about other people’s survival, to listen to and share music as a form of healing, and to find new binge-worthy but safe things to watch when i was feeling extra low. when i struggled to find such a space, i decided to make it myself. my hope is that the space will help people (or even 1 person) in their path to recovery and strength after sexual assault.🌿💐💗🦈🤝 *life continues after is a communal space for survivors of sexual assault, featuring advice, articles and arts. the space will exist for survivors to share common experiences and coping mechanisms they have learnt in their recovery. this space was created to help people who feel lost, lonely or failed by the system in the weeks, months and years following sexual assault.*🌿 - catriona”
❣️

text:
did you know that we now run a supporters group in hastings and in eastbourne?
💜
it is a safe and confidential space for supporters of anyone who has had unwanted sexual experiences. come together to share strategies and insight on helping loved ones cope with similar issues.
💜
before joining your first session at the group, there’s a 90 minute workshop to attend. this will look at the possible impact of these experiences on the person you care about, but also how this might impact on you.
💜
if you are interested in attending please email admin@survivorsnetwork.org.uk or call 01273 203380, stating which area you are based in.
💜
hastings: 11th march, 8th april, 13th may, 10th june, 8th july
location: hastings fire station bohemia road hastings tn34 1ex
💜
eastbourne:  21st february, 21st march, 18th april, 16th may, 20th june
location: café north, eastbourne, bn21 3hg
💜
#metoo #support #community #hastings #eastbourne

text:
i spent only 3 hours on the trail today. my plan was 3-4 more hours but i encountered a state park worker who left me feeling vulnerable and scared. 
i had just finished a trail that was a snow shoe trail and took an incline leading to a ski trail. i walked far left on the trail so i wouldn’t disturb the ski trail. my only goal was to get to the next sign to proceed forward. 
then the encounter happened. the snow tractor was behind me and the man (tom) yelled at me while passing me. i had no clue what he was saying so he stopped and yelled at me. he was aggressive and told me i was not listening to him. i was on the ski path which i had to be on for a bit to get to the next sign. i cried while yelling at him. i proceeded forward and he saw me fall in knee deep snow. he drove right pass me. i walked 3 miles in knee deep snow to get to the parking lot. he seemed like he was following me.

when i got to the office, he was there with his boss. the boss immediately told me i was breaking the rules. i again mentioned i was not intentionally trying to break the rules. it was obvious that both men sided with each other. the woman at the front desk showed me sympathy and told me sorry. she then mentioned to tell the boss that this was not the first time there was a complaint against tom. 
i left there feeling so angry and strong. i stood up for myself. if they don’t want runners at this state park, they should make it clear on their site. i will file another complaint on the boss as well.

never thought i would feel so vulnerable, scared and strong on the trail today.

i’m home now.  keep scrolling to see more pics.

much love ❤️ #minnesotastateparks #harassment #ultratraining #ultrarunner #50miletraining #trailrunner #vulnerable #standingupformyself #womenstrong #strongresilientindigenous #momrunner #pubiclands #ultrarunner #navajo #lost #metoo #scared

text:
feliz domingo para tod@s !
hoy acabo de despertar feliz,luminosa y agradecida, porque cuando tú cambias, todo cambia! 
la palabra lealtad según la rae es un "sentimiento de respeto y fidelidad a los propios principios morales, a los compromisos establecidos o hacia alguien"...agrega : "la lealtad es un compromiso, y por lo tanto solo pueden ser leales aquellos que están lo suficientemente maduros para asumirlos".
entonces la primera lealtad es con dios todopoderoso y su palabra, luego viene la lealtad conmigo misma que es la base de mi bienestar y mi paz : si mantengo lealtad con mis valores, principios,sentimientos y metas solo voy a generar palabras,pensamientos y acciones coherentes y llenos de positiva abundancia.
lo que no resuene o vibre en esta dirección irá progresivamente alejándose hasta desaparecer sin trauma,sin dolor,sin resentimiento, pues será para dar paso a lo que sí debe ocupar ese lugar !
deja a dios actuar,suéltate en sus manos y confía.no se trata de soltar a nadie,sino de soltarnos a nosotros mismos y del resto dios todopoderoso se encarga! confía, si tú haces tu parte, recibirás lo que te corresponde. siente la libertad de ser !
#mujeremprendedora

text:
京都にある性被害の自助グループ「mint（ミント）」3月の活動予定のお知らせです❤︎
.
.
【self help group】
.
2019年3月17日（日）
13:00〜16:00
.
.
女性として生きる中で感じていることを気軽に話せる場所です。批判やアドバイスはせず、話すほうも聞くほうもお互いにありのままで受け止めます。主に性的なトラウマを抱える女性（女性の心をもつ方）を対象としていますが、性被害のご経験の有無に関わらず女性として生きてきた中で向き合いたいことやお話ししたいことがあるときに足を運んでみてくださいね。
.
（場所）
京都駅中央改札口より徒歩約12分
「しんらん交流館」1f会議室
.
（参加費）
500円  献金制
.
（お申し込み）
参加ご希望の方は下記①〜④の事項を添えてメールにてお申し込みください。折り返しご連絡いたします。
①メールの件名「ミント参加希望」
②お名前（ニックネーム可）
③メールアドレス
④ご希望の日程
selfhelpgroup.mint@gmail.com
.
会場へのアクセスなど自助グループについて詳細はプロフィール欄（ @selfhelpgroup_mint ）ホームページの「self help group」をご覧ください。
.
.
【online salon】
.
2019年3月26日（火） meeting
.
.
遠方の方や直接会うことに抵抗がある場合はオンラインサロンでもお話しすることができます。月に1回のミーティングのほか、お気に入りの音楽や写真をアップしたり自分の体験を綴ったり、ネット上に開設した当事者のためのサロンです。（サロンは性被害のご経験をもつ女性（女性の心をもつ方）専用としております。）
.
オンラインサロンについての詳細はプロフィール欄（ @selfhelpgroup_mint ）ホームページの「online salon」をご覧ください。
.
.
お話しできることを楽しみにしています(*^^*)
.
self help group「mint」
野間千華子
.
.
.

text:
i struggle with this. especially in the last year, as i gotten older, i realize just how much my mind and body needs more  exercise, in a place that's free of distractions. i work out 4 days a week during the workweek  on my lunch break and 3 sundays ago,  josh said to me "go work out." i said no, its sunday. we have to do something fun with sawyer. he said go do something for yourself. and it has settled into my weekly sunday self care session with, just me, @turnstyleboston  and my therapist/instructor, magggz. last night, i told josh that i feel guilty for admitting how much i enjoy it.

moms, go make time for you doing the things that make you feel like you inside  #selfcare #momlife #metoo #exercise #youreworthit #thankfulformyhusband

text:
💻⌨basic computer class 💻
believe it or not,  we started with zero budget. we don't have any fund. 
we start with the kindness,  passion and blessings of god. 
god is love. thanks to those who love god and accommodate us without charges,  free internet, free room,  electric, furniture. 
in it age,  we want to equip refugees with it skills and knowledge. 
one of the refugees said that "i have been looking for an opportunity to learn but i couldn't find a place to learn. thank you very much. "  their passion in learning drives the organizer,  donors and teachers to conduct further trainings. 
special thanks to methodist college kuala lumpur, pastor michael moey and ruth education center, teachers and volunteers. thank to ourselves 🙏💞💃💃

text:
on april 16, 2017, in the village of shambhupura in banswara, rajasthan, india, kachru, 21, and monica, 19, got married and were cousins but there family, was not fine with it. the couple were paraded naked, beaten, and sexually assaulted by the whole village of shambhupura and family members including their fathers, brothers and, uncles. the accused have been booked for rioting, wrongful restraint and confinement, wrongly causing hurt, attempted murder, and sexual harassment.
-

text:
(contd) we all know someone who has been abused in this way and it causes as much, if not more damage,
than any other type of abuse - one of the worst things they do is seek to divide and conquer and pit people against each other to further isolate the victim - they rip relationships apart to the point where the distrust and wounds they create may never recover and the victim feels even more that they cannot leave. i just wanted to write this to spotlight this issue (the whole #metoo movement has shown how hard it has been for people to speak out against something that has been going on for years and emotional abuse is no different) and also to say it’s not just women but men who suffer from this kind of abuse. if you know someone that may be under the influence of a narcissist, when they finally realise what is happening to them, let them know you are there no matter how they may have behaved beforehand. they were not themselves. dont turn a blind eye to keep the peace or for harmony - you are only helping the abuser. do something.  also shout out to sparkle who went out of her way and destroyed herself to speak the truth - she was not supported by society or her family - she was estranged from them for over ten years because she spoke out-  and even derailed her own career but she had to speak it anyway. i believe her. and i hope she gets some kind of long overdue karmic justice for doing so. #survivingrkelly #feminism #thoughts #mentalhealthawareness #muterkelly

tran thi ngai, a nurse in the local village, was 24 when she was raped for the first time by a south korean soldier. she was still a virgin. her family would not believe she was raped.
the solider who initially raped mrs ngai directed two of his fellow soldiers to her over the course of the next two years. “they felt that they could help themselves; that i was fair game,” says mrs ngai.

text:
today, we are lifting up the rev. viviana thomas-breitfeld, bishop of the northwest synod of wisconsin in the elca. she was the second black woman elected in the elca, just hours after the rev. patricia davenport (featured earlier this week). when asked about her election, rev. thomas-breitfelt said, “probably the thing that has been most gratifying and most humbling is hearing from my sister-pastors and sisters who are in the call process who have been so emotional about this... it gives them a sign of hope. that as they watch me, they can celebrate and say, 'maybe that can be me, too, one of these days. maybe things are changing.'" (cp)

in an interview of rev. thomas-breitfeld, rev. davenport and four other women ecla bishops by the religious news service, rev. breitfeld was asked about the importance of women pastors during the #metoo movement. she answered, “as one of the young people said to me at the youth gathering in houston, ‘i can actually stay in this church.’ there’s that sense that people who don’t have the same picture — the white guy of a certain age — can be in leadership. that brings a sense of hope to so many, especially those who are younger.” (rns)

she says, “i hope i can help the synod become more open to change, so we can become more relevant to all, especially people of color, lgbtqi, and young adults, many of whom are choosing to not attend church,” (bcn)

when asked about whether the church is beginning to lean left, she said, “we’re reminded that jesus was political. he wasn’t partisan. god is not a republican or democrat or independent. god is god. jesus called out issues of how the poor, how the widow were being treated. that wasn’t a partisan issue. that was a gospel issue. i think of (episcopal bishop) michael curry, who is often heard to say when he is preaching, ‘i’m not preaching politics; i’m preaching jesus.’ i think that we as the elca are becoming more comfortable with preaching jesus. we are in the world. we are church together. and that is vital for us in terms of moving forward.” (rns)

that’ll preach! we’re so glad to learn more about this incredible woman! (sources below.) #blackwomenoffaith #thehiveapiary

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
christopher wylie, who worked with a cambridge university academic to obtain the data, told the observer: “we exploited facebook to harvest millions of people’s profiles. and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.” documents seen by the observer, and confirmed by a facebook statement, show that by late 2015 the company had found out that information had been harvested on an unprecedented scale. however, at the time it failed to alert users and took only limited steps to recover and secure the private information of more than 50 million individuals.

the data was collected through an app called thisisyourdigitallife, built by academic aleksandr kogan, separately from his work at cambridge university. through his company global science research (gsr), in collaboration with cambridge analytica, hundreds of thousands of users were paid to take a personality test and agreed to have their data collected for academic use.

however, the app also collected the information of the test-takers’ facebook friends, leading to the accumulation of a data pool tens of millions-strong. facebook’s “platform policy” allowed only collection of friends’ data to improve user experience in the app and barred it being sold on or used for advertising. the discovery of the unprecedented data harvesting, and the use to which it was put, raises urgent new questions about facebook’s role in targeting voters in the us presidential election. it comes only weeks after indictments of 13 russians by the special counsel robert mueller which stated they had used the platform to perpetrate “information warfare” against the us.

carole cadwalladr & emma graham-harrison
the guardian

text:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaign’s use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of people’s profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there “could have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheating”. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesday’s hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‘ugh. totally ugly’ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it’s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don’t necessarily know it’s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it’s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you’re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people’s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn’t have seen, and couldn’t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, “would work for anyone”. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they’re mercenaries. they’ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it’s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing – at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public – our intimate family connections, our “likes”, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that’s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian
